ons of the world in recent years. He focuses primarily on collective violence in the form of civilian "riots" in South Asia, using selected instances in Sri Lanka, Pakistan, and India. He situates these riots in the larger political, economic, and religious contexts in which they took place and also examines the strategic actions and motivations of their principal agents. In applying a wide range of social theory to the problems of ethnic and religious violence, Tambiah pays close attention to the history and culture of the region.On one level this provocative book is a scrupulously detailed anthropological and historical study, but on another it is an attempt to understand the social and political changes needed for a more humane order, not just in South Asia, but throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunalismzSouth Asia. 0aCrowdszSouth Asia. 0aRiotszSouth Asia. 0aViolencezSouth Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aasia.  acitizen activists.  acollective behavior.  acollective violence.  acultural history.  aethnic conflict.  aethnic studies.  aethnic violence.  ahistory.  aindia.  amassacres.  amob violence.  amobs.  amodernity.  anationalism.  anonfiction.  apakistan.  areligion.  areligious conflict.  areligious identity.  areligious violence.  arevolution.  ariots.  asocial theory.  asouth asia.  asri lanka.  astate power.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020642740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918191?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918191423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918191/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  Univers